as an opportunity. Avoiding reductionistic solutions, and without losing sight of how our lives and those of others are caught up in the moral webs we humans spin, this book skillfully fashions new kinds of conceptual tools from the strange and unexpected properties of the living world itself. In this groundbreaking work, Kohn takes anthropology in a new and exciting direction–one that offers a more capacious way to think about the world we share with other kinds of beings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEthnoecologyzAmazon River Region. 0aHuman-animal relationshipszAmazon River Region. 0aHuman-plant relationshipszAmazon River Region. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEcologyzAmazon River Region. 0aPhilosophy of naturezAmazon River Region. 0aQuechua IndiansxSocial life and customs. 0aQuechua mythology. 0aSemioticszAmazon River Region. 0aSocial scienceszAmazon River RegionxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aamazonian tribe.  aanimal and plant sentience.  aanthropologist.  aanthropology.  aarborist.  ado dogs dream.  aecology.  aenvironmentalism.  aenvironmentalist.  aethnographic.  aethnography.  anatural history.  apolitical activism.  areductionistic solution.  aruna of ecuador.  asocial activist.  aupper amazon.  awhat does it mean to be human.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027610940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095686540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520956865423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520956865/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY